translated: Celander, John Ivar Thorsten, school teacher, Jönköping, born December 6, 1876 in Fristad, Älvsborg county. Son of elementary school teacher Sven Johan C. and Rebecka Thyrén. Married in 1917 to philology graduate Vivi Högbom. Children: Hjördis, born in 1919, philology graduate, and Ivar, born in 1922, engineer. Completed secondary education at Gothenburg's higher real in 1898, and studied philology in Gothenburg in 1905. Completed a specialized course for students at Gothenburg's school of commerce, attended a trial school year at Norra Latin in Stockholm from 1905-1906. Traveled to Germany in 1903 and 1912, to England in 1920, 1923, 1924, 1926, and 1927, and to France in 1929. Taught at Stockholm's forges school and Påhlmans commercial institute from 1905-1908, was a substitute teacher at Östra real in Stockholm from 1906-1908, acted as a substitute and part-time teacher for Latin at Gothenburg's higher Latin school from 1908-1913, and as teacher of German and Swedish at Jönköping's higher secondary school from 1913 until retirement. He served as secretary for Gothenburg's higher Latin school from 1908-1913, director of Jönköping's higher secondary school from 1913-1917, and was appointed to the board of the Nässjö real school as school inspector. He was a board member of the Gothenburg higher education student union from 1902-1903 and vice chairman of the British-American Swedish Society. He was also a member of the board of the Alliance Francaise in Jönköping. He wrote on the topic of Jönköping students (1920), Swedish-English and English-Swedish dictionaries (1928), and wrote pamphlets in English at the request of the STF. He also reviewed English literature and wrote articles. Awarded the Royal Order of Vasa.
